# Rust Conventions

## Tooling

- Run format checks with `cargo fmt --check`.
- Run lint checks with `cargo clippy -- -D warnings`.
- Run tests with `cargo test`.
- Run all three before marking any Ralph criterion complete.

## Language and Compatibility

- Use Rust edition 2021.
- Match MSRV to the `rmcp` crate requirement in `rust/Cargo.toml`.
- Commit `Cargo.lock` for this binary crate.

## Error Handling

- Use `thiserror` for project error enums.
- Prefer `?` for propagation.
- Do not use `unwrap()` or `expect()` in production code.
- Return actionable, user-friendly errors at MCP tool boundaries.

## Async and Runtime

- Use the `tokio` runtime.
- Use native async traits (Rust 1.75+) by default.
- Introduce `async-trait` only if required by `rmcp` APIs.

## Testing

- Use `#[tokio::test]` for async tests.
- Use trait-based mocking and lightweight fake implementations.
- Do not add external mocking crates.
- Gate real OmniFocus integration tests behind `#[cfg(feature = "integration")]`.

## Code Organization

- Keep `src/main.rs` as the binary entry point.
- Keep shared implementation in `src/lib.rs` and re-export modules there.
- Use `src/tools/` with one file per tool entity domain.
- Avoid cross-module circular dependencies; depend on traits where possible.

## JXA Rules in Rust

- Follow `.cursor/rules/jxa-scripting.mdc` exactly.
- Escape user-controlled strings with `serde_json::to_string()`.
- Use raw string literals for multi-line script templates.
- Use the outer `evaluateJavascript` bridge pattern with OmniJS try/catch + JSON envelope.
- Preserve JXA script behavior parity between implementations.
